➤ From a DevOps perspective, this is usually due to environment differences, configuration issues, or infrastructure gaps.
➤ Environment mismatch - Dev and Prod configs (env vars, secrets, endpoints) are different.
➤ Secrets issue - Missing or incorrect secrets (DB creds, API keys) in production.
➤ Resource limits - CPU/memory limits in Prod may cause pods to crash (OOMKilled).
➤ Image/version mismatch - Different image tags or outdated images deployed in Prod.
➤ Database / dependency access - Prod services may not have access to DB, cache, or external APIs.
➤ Networking issues - Security groups, firewall rules, or Kubernetes network policies blocking traffic.
➤ Ingress / Load Balancer config - Wrong routing, host rules, or SSL issues.
➤ Scaling differences - Works with 1 replica in Dev but fails under load in Prod.
➤ Feature flags / configs - Some features enabled only in Prod causing failures.
➤ Permissions (IAM/RBAC) - Application may not have required permissions in production.

➤ How I debug as a DevOps Engineer:
 • Check pod logs (kubectl logs)
 • Describe resources (kubectl describe pod)
 • Compare Dev vs Prod configs
 • Verify secrets, env variables
 • Check ingress / load balancer
 • Monitor metrics (CPU, memory)
